where does the phrase knock on wood come from and why do spme think that knocking on a wood gives luck here's an answer from a site called world wide words there seem to be a few suggested origins both pagan and christian where the wood would refer to the cross it's an interesting question http www worldwidewords org qa qa tou to touch wood or knock on wood is a superstition action to ward off any evil consequences or bad luck perhaps because of some recent action you ve taken or untimely boasting about your good fortune i ve never been in danger of drowning touch wood it can also be a charm to bring good luck the origin is unknown though some writers have pointed to pre christian rituals involving the spirits of sacred trees such as the oak ash holly or hawthorn there is i m told an old irish belief that you should knock on wood to let the little people know that you are thanking them for a bit of good luck there s also a belief that the knocking sound prevents the devil from hearing your unwise comments others have sought a meaning in which the wood symbolises the timber of the cross but this may be a christianisation of an older ritual it wasn t always wood that was lucky in older days iron was also thought to have magical properties and to touch iron was an equivalent preventative against ill fortune the phrase itself is relatively modern as the oldest citation for the british version of the phrase touch wood that i can find dates only from the american equivalent knock on wood is roughly contemporary with my first example from source s http www worldwidewords org qa qa tou Luck Witchcraft Magic (paranormal) Amulet Shamanism Vampire Numerology Exorcism Christianization Gesture Superstition Pysanka Magical thinking Druid Theology Virgin Birth (Christian doctrine) Midsummer Hiberno-English Theory of conduct Odin Eutheism, dystheism, and maltheism Animism Evil Witch-hunt Bible Wicca Wood Neopaganism Atheism Social rule The D__mons Predestination Historicity of Jesu